development and electoral fortunes of the Labour Party in Britain and the Australian Labor Party from their formative years of the 1900s to the elections of 2010. Based upon extensive primary and secondary source-based research in Britain and Australia over several years, it makes a new and original contribution to the fields of labour, imperial and ‘British world’ history. The book offers the challenging conclusion that the forces of nation, empire and race exerted much greater influence upon Labour politics in both countries than suggested by ‘traditionalists’ and ‘revisionists’ alike. The book will appeal to undergraduates, postgraduates, scholars in history and politics and all those interested in and concerned with the past, present and future of Labour politics in Britain, Australia and more generally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aAustralian Labor Party.  aBritish Labour Party.  aBritish empire.  aBritish world.  aelectoral performance.  aempire.  aimperialism.  alabour movements.  alabour politics.  aloyalism.  anation.  apolitical power.  arace.  arevisionists.  asocial class.  asocial power.  atrade unions.  atraditionalists.  aworking-class politics.1 aKirk, Neville, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611813440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526118134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526118134/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles